## Day-03
SDLC (Software Development Life Cycle)

1.What is SDLC?

SDLC (Software Development Life Cycle) is a structured process used to plan, design, develop, test, deploy, and maintain software efficiently and with high quality.

It helps software teams deliver applications in a systematic, predictable, and cost-effective way.

Why do we use SDLC?
✅ To build high-quality software
✅ To reduce development cost
✅ To deliver projects on time
✅ To identify bugs early
✅ To improve team collaboration
✅ To satisfy customer requirements

2.Where is SDLC used?

SDLC is used in almost every software project, such as:

Web Applications
Mobile Applications
Banking Software
E-commerce Platforms
Healthcare Systems
Cloud Applications
Enterprise Software
DevOps Projects
Phases of SDLC

1. Planning

Plan the project before development starts.

Activities
Define project goals
Estimate budget
Identify risks
Create project schedule
Allocate resources
Output
Project Plan
Timeline
Budget

2. Requirement Analysis

Understand what the customer needs.

Activities
Gather requirements
Meet stakeholders
Analyze business needs
Create requirement documents
Output
Software Requirement Specification (SRS)

3. Design

Design the software architecture.

Activities
Database design
UI/UX design
System architecture
API design
Output
High-Level Design (HLD)
Low-Level Design (LLD)

4. Development (Coding)

Write the actual source code.

Activities
Develop features
Write clean code
Version control using Git
Code review
Output
Working software

5. Testing

Ensure the software works correctly.

Activities
Unit Testing
Integration Testing
System Testing
Performance Testing
Security Testing
User Acceptance Testing (UAT)
Output
Bug reports
Tested software

6. Deployment

Release the application to users.

Activities
Deploy to servers or cloud
Configure environments
Monitor deployment
Output
Live application

7. Maintenance

Keep the application running smoothly after release.

Activities
Fix bugs
Add new features
Improve performance
Apply security patches
Monitor application health
Output
Updated software versions
